    description: 'Pokémon\'s North American launch used two physically identical packages differentiated only by colour — a packaging strategy that made the purchase decision inherently social and implicitly required two copies for a complete experience.',
    longDescription: 'Nintendo\'s decision to launch Pokémon simultaneously in two versions with distinct packaging was both a game design decision and a retail strategy. The two boxes were identical in layout and typography — the Pokémon logo, the Nintendo Game Boy label, the version colour — differentiated only by the background hue and the version-specific mascot Pokémon on the front. Red Version featured Charizard; Blue Version featured Blastoise. This visual differentiation was minimal enough that the boxes were clearly related products rather than competitors, while being distinct enough to make version choice meaningful.\n\nThe packaging communicated the game\'s social mechanic before purchase: a child standing in a game store holding both boxes understood intuitively that the two versions implied a relationship, that owning both was possible, and that the choice between them would have consequences for which Pokémon they could encounter. The game\'s copy — "Gotta Catch \'Em All!" — was reinforced by the visible incompleteness of any single purchase. Pokémon\'s North American launch sold 200,000 copies in its first week and went on to become the bestselling Game Boy title of all time, with the version split credited as a significant driver of repeat and double purchases within peer groups.',
